 the countryŌĆÖs democracy activists. ŌĆ£I am outraged by this inhumane, bottom-feeding behavior from these low-class peddlers who deny the Republic of KoreaŌĆÖs community, basic human rights, and democratic values,ŌĆØ┬ĀLee said in a post on X. ŌĆ£They must be held accountable with┬Āthe corresponding┬Āmoral, administrative, legal, and political responsibility.ŌĆØ The Gwangju uprising, which was led by student protesters opposing ChunŌĆÖs dictatorial rule, is widely considered a pivotal moment in the democratisation of South Korea, which held its first free elections in decades in 1987. Acting on the orders of Chun, South Korean troops stormed the southwestern city of Gwangju to violently suppress student activists who had assembled to protest the military strongmanŌĆÖs takeover of the civilian government. Government figures suggest that more than 200 people were killed in the crackdown although activists and historians have estimated the true death toll to be as high as 2,300. South Korea is one of StarbucksŌĆÖs most important markets worldwide. The East Asian country is home to more than 2,000 outlets of the Seattle-based coffee chain, more than any other country apart from the United States and China.          Follow Al Jazeera English:","source":"Al Jazeera","url":"https://www.aljazeera.com/economy/2026/5/19/starbucks-korea-ceo-fired-over-promotion-that-evoked-military-crackdown","kafka_timestamp":"2026-05-19T09:52:43.406Z","ingestion_time":"2026-05-19T09:53:00.008Z"}
{"titre":"ŌĆśChina holds the cardsŌĆÖ: Why PutinŌĆÖs visit to Beijing after Trump matters","auteur":"Urooba Jamal","date_publication":"2026-05-19 09:15:24","categorie":"features","contenu":"A lack of progress in US-China talks makes Putin confident to head to Beijing, while for China, hosting the back-to-back visits is a diplomatic flex. Save Share When Russian President Vladimir Putin lands in Beijing on Tuesday evening, his official agenda will be to join his Chinese counterpart, Xi Jinping, in commemorating a quarter-century-old agreement, the unambiguously described 2001 Treaty of Good-Neighborliness and Friendly Cooperation. Yet, say analysts, the significance of the Xi-Putin summit, likely to be held on Wednesday morning, runs much deeper ŌĆö as does its timing. PutinŌĆÖs visit wasannouncedjust a day after United States President Donald TrumpŌĆÖs departure from China following the American leaderŌĆÖs summit with Xi last week. While Trumptouted broad trade deals, there is little evidence that the US and China made significant progress on the most contentious issues dividing Washington and Beijing, including Taiwan and the US-Israel war on Iran. That, say analysts, suits Putin well, allowing him to head to Beijing confident that China has no plans to sidestep its relationship with Russia. For Beijing, meanwhile, the back-to-back visits are a flex of its growing diplomatic leverage, positioning China as a central player capable of engaging rival powers on its own terms. United by Western sanctions and a view of TrumpŌĆÖs foreign policy as reckless, Putin and Xi have forged a right partnership in recent years ŌĆö and no major shifts are expected during the Russian presidentŌĆÖs visit.┬ĀBut its timing underscores how Beijing is consolidating its role at the centre of an increasingly fragmented global order, analysts say. Despite ChinaŌĆÖs posturing, no breakthroughs are expected from PutinŌĆÖs visit, but rather a continuity of their strategic relationship. ŌĆ£I donŌĆÖt think that there is going to be a major shift,ŌĆØ Marina Miron, a postdoctoral researcher in defence studies at KingŌĆÖs College London, told Al Jazeera. ŌĆ£ItŌĆÖs going to be a deepening of bilateral relations when it comes to economic cooperation, business, exchange of military technologies and so on.ŌĆØ Oleg Ignatov, a senior Russia analyst at Crisis Group, echoed that assessment. ŌĆ£The relationship between the two countries is strategic ŌĆö┬Āthey are partners, strategic partners, but they are not military allies, and I donŌĆÖt expect that they will go anywhere further,ŌĆØ he told Al Jazeera. ŌĆ£Russia and ChinaŌĆÖs relationships [are] very stable, very important for both countries, and there is no negative agenda in this relationship.ŌĆØ Both sides are expected to advance joint projects, particularly in energy. China wants access to RussiaŌĆÖs energy resources ŌĆ£at discountŌĆØ, while Russia depends on many of ChinaŌĆÖs dual-use technologies, specifically for drone production, said Miron.    Still, the meeting is more important forPutin. ŌĆ£Putin needs this more than Xi. Russia is now the junior, dependent partner, following PutinŌĆÖs disastrous war in Ukraine. Putin might be looking for increased military support from China,ŌĆØ Timothy Ash, an associate fellow at the Russia and Eurasia Programme at Chatham House, told Al Jazeera. ŌĆ£Rather as Trump went cap in hand to Beijing, so will Putin,ŌĆØ he added. ŌĆ£China has all the cards.ŌĆØ Ignatov, however, cautioned against reading the relationship through a purely hierarchical lens, stating that the countriesŌĆÖ conduct is because they are ultimately vying for a multipolar world. ŌĆ£Both sides say that ŌĆ” theyŌĆÖre going to build a multipolar world so they donŌĆÖt think there [should be] dominant powers [who] should push other countries to do something,ŌĆØ he said. ŌĆ£ThatŌĆÖs not how they look at the international relationships.ŌĆØ What makes the back-to-back summits so significant, however, is what they say about BeijingŌĆÖs broader diplomatic posture. China is positioning itself as the indispensable interlocutor in an increasingly fractured international order, the analysts said. ŌĆ£China is trying to position itself as a mediator, as a kind of neutral player ŌĆö┬Āwithout any sort of adversaries,ŌĆØ Miron said. ŌĆ£China is trying not to align itself, at least not publicly, with any superpower, despite the fact that China is much closer to Russia,ŌĆØ she added. ŌĆ£In the diplomatic sphere, theyŌĆÖre trying to display their neutrality as a kind of neutral superpower.ŌĆØ    Looming over the visit is the ongoingUS-Israel war on IranŌĆö a conflict that has shaken global energy markets by largely closing the Strait of Hormuz ŌĆö┬Āwith more consequences for ChinaŌĆÖs economy than RussiaŌĆÖs, said Miron. Russia is benefitting from the disruption in the short term, she said, with Gulf energy competitors sidelined. But analysts agree that long-term stability matters to Russia too, with both countries wanting to see an end to the conflict, even while they have shared intelligence and technology with Iran. Ash noted that Moscow will have drawn quiet satisfaction from what the Trump-Xi summit failed to produce. ŌĆ£China did not give Trump what he wanted ŌĆö┬Āan end to the Iran war,ŌĆØ he said. ŌĆ£Moscow will be content that Beijing is not going to abandon Tehran, or Moscow for that matter.ŌĆØ RussiaŌĆÖs war on Ukrainewill also almost certainly come up, but the analysts do not anticipate China pressuring Moscow towards any particular outcome. ŌĆ£Ukraine will certainly be discussed, and China will certainly say that it is for mediation and for peaceful negotiations,ŌĆØ Miron said. ŌĆ£But China is also not wishing to see Russia humiliated in any way ŌĆ” I donŌĆÖt think itŌĆÖs going to be something of an ultimatum in any way or form.ŌĆØ While the visit may not produce a profound diplomatic outcome, it has made one thing clear: Beijing, in hosting the US president one day and the Russian leader the next, has made itself impossible to ignore.          Follow Al Jazeera English:","source":"Al Jazeera","url":"https://www.aljazeera.com/features/2026/5/19/neutral-superpower-china-why-putin-visit-to-beijing-after-trump-matters","kafka_timestamp":"2026-05-19T09:52:43.838Z","ingestion_time":"2026-05-19T09:53:00.008Z"}
